{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1781367755930,"sessionID":"ses_13e377e8fffeBUJXd02f1iJrmW","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_AEIrpNL8sMuVehzqXHg2RH51","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/148-sk-interface-design/002-ui-ux-pro-max-merge-research/research/lineages/gpt55fast/.executor-state","offset":1,"limit":200},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/148-sk-interface-design/002-ui-ux-pro-max-merge-research/research/lineages/gpt55fast/.executor-state</path>\n<type>directory</type>\n<entries>\n\n\n(0 entries)\n</entries>","metadata":{"preview":"","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"directory","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/148-sk-interface-design/002-ui-ux-pro-max-merge-research/research/lineages/gpt55fast/.executor-state","entries":[],"offset":1,"totalEntries":0,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/148-sk-interface-design/002-ui-ux-pro-max-merge-research/research/lineages/gpt55fast/.executor-state","time":{"start":1781367755919,"end":1781367755928}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_09c9e28230c26120016a2d83cbd0a88191b9b19f6dd0417107"}},"id":"prt_ec1cad462001sXPH80jF8ptGYk","sessionID":"ses_13e377e8fffeBUJXd02f1iJrmW","messageID":"msg_ec1caa389001VvtTL4IUCjJcnX"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1781367756093,"sessionID":"ses_13e377e8fffeBUJXd02f1iJrmW","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"glob","callID":"call_Nc0a72I7cZdDcN6O7clg2Wvh","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/148-sk-interface-design/external/ui-ux-pro-max-skill-main/**","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public"},"output":"No files found","metadata":{"count":0,"truncated":false},"title":"","time":{"start":1781367755940,"end":1781367756091}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_09c9e28230c26120016a2d83cbd0c481918dd1e917662f328e"}},"id":"prt_ec1cad49c001cSA3Zs3B3ChXbU","sessionID":"ses_13e377e8fffeBUJXd02f1iJrmW","messageID":"msg_ec1caa389001VvtTL4IUCjJcnX"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1781367756121,"sessionID":"ses_13e377e8fffeBUJXd02f1iJrmW","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_AoHHccBGsfWtDY08Rp1IpX6V","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-interface-design/SKILL.md","offset":1,"limit":2000},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-interface-design/SKILL.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: name: sk-interface-design\n3: description: Guidance for distinctive, intentional UI design when building or reshaping an interface. Drives deliberate palette, typography, layout and motion choices that avoid templated AI defaults, with a brainstorm-critique-build process and interface writing rules.\n4: allowed-tools: [Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Grep, Glob]\n5: version: 1.0.0\n6: metadata:\n7:   author: Anthropic\n8:   source: https://github.com/anthropics/skills/tree/main/skills/frontend-design\n9: license: Apache-2.0; complete terms in LICENSE.txt\n10: ---\n11: \n12: <!-- keywords: interface-design frontend-design visual-design typography palette ui-aesthetics -->\n13: \n14: # Interface Design (sk-interface-design)\n15: \n16: Approach UI work as the design lead at a studio known for visual identities that could not be mistaken for anyone else's. Make deliberate, opinionated choices specific to the brief, take one justified aesthetic risk, and reject anything that reads as a templated default. Full guidance lives in [`references/design_principles.md`](references/design_principles.md). Vendored from Anthropic's `frontend-design` skill (Apache-2.0).\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## 1. WHEN TO USE\n21: \n22: ### Activation Triggers\n23: \n24: **Use when** the work involves:\n25: - Building a new UI, page, component, or landing section from a brief.\n26: - Reshaping or restyling an existing interface that feels generic or templated.\n27: - Choosing palette, typography, layout, motion, or interface copy.\n28: - Reviewing a design direction before code is written.\n29: \n30: **Keyword Triggers**: \"design\", \"make it look good\", \"redesign\", \"variation\", \"hero section\", \"landing page\", \"looks templated\", \"looks AI-generated\", \"visual identity\".\n31: \n32: ### When NOT to Use\n33: \n34: **Skip this skill when:**\n35: - The task is pure logic, data, or back-end work with no visual surface (use `sk-code`).\n36: - A brief already fully pins the visual direction and only mechanical implementation remains (follow the brief, since this skill adds nothing).\n37: - The work is documentation or prose, not interface (use `sk-doc`).\n38: \n39: ---\n40: \n41: ## 2. SMART ROUTING\n42: \n43: ### Primary Detection Signal\n44: \n45: Detect design intent and how much of the visual direction the brief fixes:\n46: \n47: ```bash\n48: # Direction freedom (pseudo)\n49: echo \"$BRIEF\" | grep -qiE 'palette|font|typography|layout|brand|look|style' && AXIS_PINNED=high\n50: # If the brief pins the direction -> follow it exactly. If axes are free -> apply the principles.\n51: ```\n52: \n53: ### Phase Detection\n54: \n55: ```text\n56: DESIGN TASK\n57:     |\n58:     +- STEP 0: Ground the subject (name subject, audience, the page's one job)\n59:     +- STEP 1: Brainstorm a token system (color, type, layout, signature)\n60:     +- STEP 2: Critique the plan against AI-default looks, then revise and justify\n61:     +- STEP 3: Build from the revised plan, deriving every choice from it\n62:     +- STEP 4: Self-critique (screenshot, remove one accessory, check quality floor)\n63: ```\n64: \n65: ### Resource Loading Levels\n66: \n67: | Level | When to Load | Resource |\n68: | ----- | ------------ | -------- |\n69: | ALWAYS | Any design task | `references/design_principles.md` (palette, type, structure, motion, restraint) |\n70: | CONDITIONAL | Writing UI copy | Section 6 of `design_principles.md` (writing in design) |\n71: | ON_DEMAND | Implementing in code | `sk-code` web-surface standards for the target stack |\n72: \n73: ### Smart Router Pseudocode\n74: \n75: ```python\n76: # Route a design task to the right guidance.\n77: # 1) Always load references/design_principles.md.\n78: # 2) If the brief fixes the visual direction, follow the brief verbatim and skip default-avoidance.\n79: # 3) If axes are free, apply Sections 2-5 (subject, principles, process, restraint).\n80: # 4) If the task writes interface copy, also apply Section 6 (writing).\n81: # 5) Hand implementation to sk-code for the detected web surface. This skill owns the look, not the build mechanics.\n82: ```\n83: \n84: ---\n85: \n86: ## 3. HOW IT WORKS\n87: \n88: ### The Two-Pass Process\n89: \n90: **Process Flow**:\n91: ```\n92: STEP 1: Ground the subject\n93:        └─ Name one concrete subject, its audience, and the page's single job\n94:        ↓\n95: STEP 2: Brainstorm a compact token system\n96:        ├─ Color: 4-6 named hex values\n97:        ├─ Type: a display face used with restraint + a body face (+ utility face)\n98:        ├─ Layout: a concept with one-sentence prose + ASCII wireframes\n99:        └─ Signature: the one element the page will be remembered by\n100:        ↓\n101: STEP 3: Critique the plan against the brief\n102:        └─ Anything that reads like a generic default gets revised, with a stated reason\n103:        ↓\n104: STEP 4: Build from the revised plan\n105:        └─ Derive every color and type decision from the plan, mind CSS specificity\n106:        ↓\n107: STEP 5: Self-critique\n108:        └─ Screenshot if possible, remove one accessory, confirm the quality floor\n109: ```\n110: \n111: Calibration matters: current AI design clusters around three default looks (cream + serif + terracotta, near-black + one acid accent, broadsheet with hairline rules). They are defaults, not choices. When the brief frees an axis, do not spend it on one of these. The full calibration, two-pass detail, and writing rules are in [`references/design_principles.md`](references/design_principles.md).\n112: \n113: ### Quality Floor\n114: \n115: Build to it without announcing it: responsive down to mobile, visible keyboard focus, and reduced motion respected. Do most of the planning and iteration in thinking, and show the user ideas only at higher confidence.\n116: \n117: ---\n118: \n119: ## 4. RULES\n120: \n121: ### ALWAYS\n122: \n123: 1. **ALWAYS ground the design in the subject** before choosing anything. Name the subject, audience, and the page's single job, then draw distinctive choices from the subject's own world.\n124: 2. **ALWAYS make deliberate, brief-specific choices** for palette, typography, layout, and motion, and take one justifiable aesthetic risk.\n125: 3. **ALWAYS critique the plan against the AI-default looks** before writing code, and revise anything generic with a stated reason.\n126: 4. **ALWAYS treat copy as design material**, with active voice, end-user vocabulary, and consistent action names across a flow.\n127: 5. **ALWAYS meet the quality floor**: responsive, visible focus, reduced-motion respected.\n128: \n129: ### NEVER\n130: \n131: 1. **NEVER ship a templated default** (cream + serif + terracotta, near-black + one acid accent, or broadsheet hairlines) on a free axis just because it is safe.\n132: 2. **NEVER add decoration that does not serve the brief**, including numbered markers (01 / 02 / 03) when the content is not actually a sequence.\n133: 3. **NEVER let motion pile up**. Scattered animation reads as AI-generated, so prefer one orchestrated moment.\n134: 4. **NEVER override a brief that pins the direction**. The brief's own words always win, even when they ask for a default look.\n135: \n136: ### ESCALATE IF\n137: \n138: 1. **ESCALATE IF the brief is too thin to ground** and you cannot reasonably pin the subject, audience, or page job yourself. State your assumed direction and confirm.\n139: 2. **ESCALATE IF the requested direction conflicts with brand or accessibility** (for example a palette that fails contrast). Surface the trade-off before building.\n140: \n141: ---\n142: \n143: ## 5. REFERENCES\n144: \n145: ### Core References\n146: \n147: - [`references/design_principles.md`](references/design_principles.md) - Full guidance: grounding, design principles, the two-pass process with AI-default calibration, restraint and self-critique, and interface writing.\n148: - [`LICENSE.txt`](LICENSE.txt) - Apache-2.0 license and attribution for the vendored Anthropic content.\n149: \n150: ### Reference Loading Notes\n151: \n152: - Load `design_principles.md` on every design task. It is the authority for palette, type, structure, motion, and copy.\n153: - Keep Section 2 (SMART ROUTING) as the single routing authority.\n154: \n155: ---\n156: \n157: ## 6. SUCCESS CRITERIA\n158: \n159: **A design is ready when:**\n160: - ✅ The subject, audience, and the page's single job are named.\n161: - ✅ A token system (color, type, layout, signature) exists and was critiqued against the AI-default looks.\n162: - ✅ Every color and type decision derives from the revised plan.\n163: - ✅ The signature element is the one bold move, and everything else is quiet.\n164: - ✅ The quality floor holds: responsive, visible focus, reduced motion respected.\n165: \n166: ---\n167: \n168: ## 7. INTEGRATION POINTS\n169: \n170: ### Related Skills\n171: \n172: - **`sk-code`** owns implementation. This skill decides the look, and sk-code builds it to the detected web surface's standards and verifies it.\n173: - **`sk-code-review`** can audit the built UI against the standards sk-code enforces.\n174: - **`mcp-chrome-devtools`** drives a real browser to screenshot the build for the self-critique step.\n175: \n176: ### Knowledge Base Dependencies\n177: \n178: **Required**: `references/design_principles.md`. **Conditional**: `sk-code` web-surface references for the target stack during implementation.\n179: \n180: ---\n181: \n182: ## 8. REFERENCES AND RELATED RESOURCES\n183: \n184: The router (Section 2) loads `references/design_principles.md` for every design task. Hand implementation to `sk-code`, use `mcp-chrome-devtools` for screenshot-based self-critique, and reach for `system-spec-kit` when the work needs packet documentation.\n185: \n186: Upstream: vendored from [anthropics/skills/skills/frontend-design](https://github.com/anthropics/skills/tree/main/skills/frontend-design) under Apache-2.0. `LICENSE.txt` carries the full terms.\n\n(End of file - total 186 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nname: sk-interface-design\ndescription: Guidance for distinctive, intentional UI design when building or reshaping an interface. Drives deliberate palette, typography, layout and motion choices that avoid templated AI defaults, with a brainstorm-critique-build process and interface writing rules.\nallowed-tools: [Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Grep, Glob]\nversion: 1.0.0\nmetadata:\n  author: Anthropic\n  source: https://github.com/anthropics/skills/tree/main/skills/frontend-design\nlicense: Apache-2.0; complete terms in LICENSE.txt\n---\n\n<!-- keywords: interface-design frontend-design visual-design typography palette ui-aesthetics -->\n\n# Interface Design (sk-interface-design)\n\nApproach UI work as the design lead at a studio known for visual identities that could not be mistaken for anyone else's. Make deliberate, opinionated choices specific to the brief, take one justified aesthetic risk, and reject anything that reads as a templated default. Full guidance lives in [`references/design_principles.md`](references/design_principles.md). Vendored from Anthropic's `frontend-design` skill (Apache-2.0).\n\n---\n\n## 1. WHEN TO USE","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-interface-design/SKILL.md","text":"---\nname: sk-interface-design\ndescription: Guidance for distinctive, intentional UI design when building or reshaping an interface. Drives deliberate palette, typography, layout and motion choices that avoid templated AI defaults, with a brainstorm-critique-build process and interface writing rules.\nallowed-tools: [Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Grep, Glob]\nversion: 1.0.0\nmetadata:\n  author: Anthropic\n  source: https://github.com/anthropics/skills/tree/main/skills/frontend-design\nlicense: Apache-2.0; complete terms in LICENSE.txt\n---\n\n<!-- keywords: interface-design frontend-design visual-design typography palette ui-aesthetics -->\n\n# Interface Design (sk-interface-design)\n\nApproach UI work as the design lead at a studio known for visual identities that could not be mistaken for anyone else's. Make deliberate, opinionated choices specific to the brief, take one justified aesthetic risk, and reject anything that reads as a templated default. Full guidance lives in [`references/design_principles.md`](references/design_principles.md). Vendored from Anthropic's `frontend-design` skill (Apache-2.0).\n\n---\n\n## 1. WHEN TO USE\n\n### Activation Triggers\n\n**Use when** the work involves:\n- Building a new UI, page, component, or landing section from a brief.\n- Reshaping or restyling an existing interface that feels generic or templated.\n- Choosing palette, typography, layout, motion, or interface copy.\n- Reviewing a design direction before code is written.\n\n**Keyword Triggers**: \"design\", \"make it look good\", \"redesign\", \"variation\", \"hero section\", \"landing page\", \"looks templated\", \"looks AI-generated\", \"visual identity\".\n\n### When NOT to Use\n\n**Skip this skill when:**\n- The task is pure logic, data, or back-end work with no visual surface (use `sk-code`).\n- A brief already fully pins the visual direction and only mechanical implementation remains (follow the brief, since this skill adds nothing).\n- The work is documentation or prose, not interface (use `sk-doc`).\n\n---\n\n## 2. SMART ROUTING\n\n### Primary Detection Signal\n\nDetect design intent and how much of the visual direction the brief fixes:\n\n```bash\n# Direction freedom (pseudo)\necho \"$BRIEF\" | grep -qiE 'palette|font|typography|layout|brand|look|style' && AXIS_PINNED=high\n# If the brief pins the direction -> follow it exactly. If axes are free -> apply the principles.\n```\n\n### Phase Detection\n\n```text\nDESIGN TASK\n    |\n    +- STEP 0: Ground the subject (name subject, audience, the page's one job)\n    +- STEP 1: Brainstorm a token system (color, type, layout, signature)\n    +- STEP 2: Critique the plan against AI-default looks, then revise and justify\n    +- STEP 3: Build from the revised plan, deriving every choice from it\n    +- STEP 4: Self-critique (screenshot, remove one accessory, check quality floor)\n```\n\n### Resource Loading Levels\n\n| Level | When to Load | Resource |\n| ----- | ------------ | -------- |\n| ALWAYS | Any design task | `references/design_principles.md` (palette, type, structure, motion, restraint) |\n| CONDITIONAL | Writing UI copy | Section 6 of `design_principles.md` (writing in design) |\n| ON_DEMAND | Implementing in code | `sk-code` web-surface standards for the target stack |\n\n### Smart Router Pseudocode\n\n```python\n# Route a design task to the right guidance.\n# 1) Always load references/design_principles.md.\n# 2) If the brief fixes the visual direction, follow the brief verbatim and skip default-avoidance.\n# 3) If axes are free, apply Sections 2-5 (subject, principles, process, restraint).\n# 4) If the task writes interface copy, also apply Section 6 (writing).\n# 5) Hand implementation to sk-code for the detected web surface. This skill owns the look, not the build mechanics.\n```\n\n---\n\n## 3. HOW IT WORKS\n\n### The Two-Pass Process\n\n**Process Flow**:\n```\nSTEP 1: Ground the subject\n       └─ Name one concrete subject, its audience, and the page's single job\n       ↓\nSTEP 2: Brainstorm a compact token system\n       ├─ Color: 4-6 named hex values\n       ├─ Type: a display face used with restraint + a body face (+ utility face)\n       ├─ Layout: a concept with one-sentence prose + ASCII wireframes\n       └─ Signature: the one element the page will be remembered by\n       ↓\nSTEP 3: Critique the plan against the brief\n       └─ Anything that reads like a generic default gets revised, with a stated reason\n       ↓\nSTEP 4: Build from the revised plan\n       └─ Derive every color and type decision from the plan, mind CSS specificity\n       ↓\nSTEP 5: Self-critique\n       └─ Screenshot if possible, remove one accessory, confirm the quality floor\n```\n\nCalibration matters: current AI design clusters around three default looks (cream + serif + terracotta, near-black + one acid accent, broadsheet with hairline rules). They are defaults, not choices. When the brief frees an axis, do not spend it on one of these. The full calibration, two-pass detail, and writing rules are in [`references/design_principles.md`](references/design_principles.md).\n\n### Quality Floor\n\nBuild to it without announcing it: responsive down to mobile, visible keyboard focus, and reduced motion respected. Do most of the planning and iteration in thinking, and show the user ideas only at higher confidence.\n\n---\n\n## 4. RULES\n\n### ALWAYS\n\n1. **ALWAYS ground the design in the subject** before choosing anything. Name the subject, audience, and the page's single job, then draw distinctive choices from the subject's own world.\n2. **ALWAYS make deliberate, brief-specific choices** for palette, typography, layout, and motion, and take one justifiable aesthetic risk.\n3. **ALWAYS critique the plan against the AI-default looks** before writing code, and revise anything generic with a stated reason.\n4. **ALWAYS treat copy as design material**, with active voice, end-user vocabulary, and consistent action names across a flow.\n5. **ALWAYS meet the quality floor**: responsive, visible focus, reduced-motion respected.\n\n### NEVER\n\n1. **NEVER ship a templated default** (cream + serif + terracotta, near-black + one acid accent, or broadsheet hairlines) on a free axis just because it is safe.\n2. **NEVER add decoration that does not serve the brief**, including numbered markers (01 / 02 / 03) when the content is not actually a sequence.\n3. **NEVER let motion pile up**. Scattered animation reads as AI-generated, so prefer one orchestrated moment.\n4. **NEVER override a brief that pins the direction**. The brief's own words always win, even when they ask for a default look.\n\n### ESCALATE IF\n\n1. **ESCALATE IF the brief is too thin to ground** and you cannot reasonably pin the subject, audience, or page job yourself. State your assumed direction and confirm.\n2. **ESCALATE IF the requested direction conflicts with brand or accessibility** (for example a palette that fails contrast). Surface the trade-off before building.\n\n---\n\n## 5. REFERENCES\n\n### Core References\n\n- [`references/design_principles.md`](references/design_principles.md) - Full guidance: grounding, design principles, the two-pass process with AI-default calibration, restraint and self-critique, and interface writing.\n- [`LICENSE.txt`](LICENSE.txt) - Apache-2.0 license and attribution for the vendored Anthropic content.\n\n### Reference Loading Notes\n\n- Load `design_principles.md` on every design task. It is the authority for palette, type, structure, motion, and copy.\n- Keep Section 2 (SMART ROUTING) as the single routing authority.\n\n---\n\n## 6. SUCCESS CRITERIA\n\n**A design is ready when:**\n- ✅ The subject, audience, and the page's single job are named.\n- ✅ A token system (color, type, layout, signature) exists and was critiqued against the AI-default looks.\n- ✅ Every color and type decision derives from the revised plan.\n- ✅ The signature element is the one bold move, and everything else is quiet.\n- ✅ The quality floor holds: responsive, visible focus, reduced motion respected.\n\n---\n\n## 7. INTEGRATION POINTS\n\n### Related Skills\n\n- **`sk-code`** owns implementation. This skill decides the look, and sk-code builds it to the detected web surface's standards and verifies it.\n- **`sk-code-review`** can audit the built UI against the standards sk-code enforces.\n- **`mcp-chrome-devtools`** drives a real browser to screenshot the build for the self-critique step.\n\n### Knowledge Base Dependencies\n\n**Required**: `references/design_principles.md`. **Conditional**: `sk-code` web-surface references for the target stack during implementation.\n\n---\n\n## 8. REFERENCES AND RELATED RESOURCES\n\nThe router (Section 2) loads `references/design_principles.md` for every design task. Hand implementation to `sk-code`, use `mcp-chrome-devtools` for screenshot-based self-critique, and reach for `system-spec-kit` when the work needs packet documentation.\n\nUpstream: vendored from [anthropics/skills/skills/frontend-design](https://github.com/anthropics/skills/tree/main/skills/frontend-design) under Apache-2.0. `LICENSE.txt` carries the full terms.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":186,"totalLines":186,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-interface-design/SKILL.md","time":{"start":1781367756042,"end":1781367756111}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_09c9e28230c26120016a2d83cbd0d48191b08ca689e096ae72"}},"id":"prt_ec1cad4d0001mRpKIYZ4PkWqDf","sessionID":"ses_13e377e8fffeBUJXd02f1iJrmW","messageID":"msg_ec1caa389001VvtTL4IUCjJcnX"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1781367756121,"sessionID":"ses_13e377e8fffeBUJXd02f1iJrmW","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_BwkvFIah185bCrSc9nsjO3zL","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-interface-design/README.md","offset":1,"limit":1600},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-interface-design/README.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: sk-interface-design\n3: description: Aesthetic-direction skill for distinctive, intentional UI. Drives palette, typography, layout and motion choices that avoid templated AI defaults, then hands implementation to sk-code.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"interface design\"\n6:   - \"frontend design\"\n7:   - \"make it look good\"\n8:   - \"looks templated\"\n9:   - \"redesign\"\n10: ---\n11: \n12: # sk-interface-design\n13: \n14: > Design interfaces that could not be mistaken for anyone else's: deliberate palette, typography, layout and motion grounded in the brief, with a critique pass that kills templated AI defaults before a line of code is written.\n15: \n16: ---\n17: \n18: ## 1. AT A GLANCE\n19: \n20: | Aspect | What you get |\n21: |---|---|\n22: | **Use it for** | Aesthetic direction when building or reshaping UI: palette, typography, layout, motion, signature element, and interface copy |\n23: | **Invoke with** | \"interface design\", \"make it look good\", \"redesign\", \"looks templated\", \"hero section\" or auto-routing on design intent |\n24: | **Works on** | Any front-end surface, pairing with `sk-code` for implementation and `mcp-chrome-devtools` for screenshot self-critique |\n25: | **Produces** | A grounded design plan (token system + signature) critiqued against AI-default looks, then built to a responsive, accessible quality floor |\n26: \n27: ---\n28: \n29: ## 2. OVERVIEW\n30: \n31: ### Why This Skill Exists\n32: \n33: AI-generated UI clusters around a handful of default looks that appear regardless of subject: cream-and-serif-and-terracotta, near-black-with-one-acid-accent, broadsheet-hairlines. They are safe, and they are why generated designs read as templated. A model building UI without explicit direction reaches for those defaults and for scattered motion that signals \"AI made this.\" This skill gives the framework a reusable, advisor-routable point of view: ground the design in the subject, make deliberate choices, take one justified risk, and critique the plan before building.\n34: \n35: ### What It Does\n36: \n37: The skill owns aesthetic direction, not implementation. It routes a design task through a two-pass process: ground the subject, brainstorm a compact token system (4-6 named colors, a display and body face, a layout concept, one signature element), then critique that plan against the known AI-default looks and revise anything generic with a stated reason. Only then does code get written, deriving every choice from the revised plan. It also carries interface-writing rules, because copy can make a design feel as templated as the visuals. Implementation is handed to `sk-code`, which builds and verifies against the detected web surface.\n38: \n39: This is vendored from Anthropic's `frontend-design` skill (Apache-2.0). The full design guidance lives verbatim in `references/design_principles.md`, and the `SKILL.md` is a lean house-template router over it.\n40: \n41: ---\n42: \n43: ## 3. QUICK START\n44: \n45: **Step 1: Let the advisor route a design task here, or read the skill directly.**\n46: \n47: ```bash\n48: # The advisor surfaces this skill on design intent. To read it directly:\n49: cat .opencode/skills/sk-interface-design/SKILL.md\n50: ```\n51: \n52: **Step 2: Ground the subject and brainstorm a token system.**\n53: \n54: Name one concrete subject, its audience, and the page's single job. Then draft a compact plan:\n55: \n56: ```text\n57: Color:     4-6 named hex values drawn from the subject's world\n58: Type:      a characterful display face (used with restraint) + a body face\n59: Layout:    a one-sentence concept + an ASCII wireframe\n60: Signature: the single element the page will be remembered by\n61: ```\n62: \n63: **Step 3: Critique against the defaults, then build.**\n64: \n65: ```text\n66: For each part of the plan, ask: would I produce this for any similar brief?\n67: If yes, it is a default, not a choice. Revise it and say what changed and why.\n68: Then build from the revised plan and hand implementation to sk-code.\n69: ```\n70: \n71: Full guidance: [`references/design_principles.md`](./references/design_principles.md).\n72: \n73: ---\n74: \n75: ## 4. HOW IT WORKS\n76: \n77: ### The Two-Pass Process\n78: \n79: The skill never jumps straight to code. It grounds the subject, brainstorms a token system, and critiques that plan against three known AI-default looks before building. Anything that reads as a generic default gets revised with a stated reason, and every color and type decision in the build derives from the revised plan.\n80: \n81: ### Restraint Is The Mechanism\n82: \n83: Boldness is spent in one place. The signature element is the one memorable move and everything around it stays quiet and disciplined. Decoration that does not serve the brief is cut, including numbered markers when the content is not actually a sequence, and motion that piles up rather than serving one orchestrated moment. The build meets a quiet quality floor: responsive to mobile, visible keyboard focus, reduced motion respected.\n84: \n85: ### Copy Is Design Material\n86: \n87: Words exist to make an interface easier to use. The skill writes from the end user's side of the screen in active voice, keeps action names consistent across a flow, and treats errors and empty states as direction rather than mood.\n88: \n89: ### Where The Detail Lives\n90: \n91: `references/design_principles.md` holds the verbatim guidance: grounding, the full design principles, the two-pass process with the AI-default calibration, restraint and self-critique, and interface writing.\n92: \n93: ---\n94: \n95: ## 5. INTEGRATION & NAVIGATION\n96: \n97: ### When To Use This Skill\n98: \n99: Reach for it whenever a task has a visual surface and the look should feel intentional: a new page or component, a redesign, a section variation, or any \"make it look good\" request. Skip it for pure logic or back-end work, and defer to the brief when the brief already pins the visual direction.\n100: \n101: ### Related Skills\n102: \n103: | Skill | Relationship |\n104: |---|---|\n105: | `sk-code` | Owns implementation. This skill sets the look, and sk-code builds it to the detected web surface's standards and verifies it. |\n106: | `sk-code-review` | Audits the built UI against the standards sk-code enforces. |\n107: | `mcp-chrome-devtools` | Drives a real browser to screenshot the build for the self-critique step. |\n108: \n109: ---\n110: \n111: ## 6. TROUBLESHOOTING\n112: \n113: | What you see | Why | Fix |\n114: |---|---|---|\n115: | The output still looks templated | The plan was not critiqued against the AI-default looks, or a free axis was spent on a default | Run the critique pass in `design_principles.md` Section 4, then revise each generic part with a stated reason |\n116: | The design feels busy or \"AI-made\" | Boldness was spread across many elements, or motion piled up | Spend boldness on one signature element, cut one accessory, reduce to one orchestrated motion moment |\n117: | Copy undercuts the design | Labels describe the system, not what the user controls | Apply `design_principles.md` Section 6: active voice, end-user vocabulary, consistent action names |\n118: | The brief asked for a \"default\" look and the skill fought it | The brief's direction always wins | Follow the brief verbatim, since default-avoidance applies only to free axes |\n119: \n120: ---\n121: \n122: ## 7. FAQ\n123: \n124: **Q: Does this skill write the code?**\n125: \n126: A: No. It owns aesthetic direction and the design plan. `sk-code` owns implementation and verification for the detected web surface. The two pair: design here, build there.\n127: \n128: **Q: What are the \"AI-default looks\" it avoids?**\n129: \n130: A: Three clusters that appear regardless of subject: cream background with a high-contrast serif and terracotta accent, near-black with one bright acid accent, broadsheet hairlines with zero radius. They are legitimate for some briefs but are defaults, not choices. On a free axis, the skill does not spend it on one of these.\n131: \n132: **Q: What if the brief already specifies the look?**\n133: \n134: A: The brief wins, verbatim, even when it asks for one of the default looks. Default-avoidance only applies to axes the brief leaves free.\n135: \n136: **Q: Where did this come from?**\n137: \n138: A: It is vendored from Anthropic's official `frontend-design` skill under Apache-2.0. `LICENSE.txt` carries the full terms and attribution, and the guidance is preserved verbatim in `references/design_principles.md`.\n139: \n140: ---\n141: \n142: ## 8. VERIFICATION\n143: \n144: | Check | How to run it |\n145: |---|---|\n146: | Skill structure | `python3 .opencode/skills/sk-doc/scripts/package_skill.py .opencode/skills/sk-interface-design/` reports the skill valid |\n147: | README structure | `python3 .opencode/skills/sk-doc/scripts/validate_document.py .opencode/skills/sk-interface-design/README.md --type readme` reports zero issues |\n148: | Reference structure | `python3 .opencode/skills/sk-doc/scripts/validate_document.py .opencode/skills/sk-interface-design/references/design_principles.md --type reference` reports zero issues |\n149: | Advisor discovery | `node .opencode/bin/skill-advisor.cjs advisor_recommend --json '{\"prompt\":\"make this landing page look distinctive\"}' --warm-only --format json` lists `sk-interface-design` |\n150: \n151: ---\n152: \n153: ## 9. RELATED DOCUMENTS\n154: \n155: | Document | Purpose |\n156: |---|---|\n157: | [`SKILL.md`](./SKILL.md) | Runtime instructions: WHEN TO USE, SMART ROUTING, HOW IT WORKS, RULES, REFERENCES (house template) |\n158: | [`references/design_principles.md`](./references/design_principles.md) | Full verbatim guidance: grounding, design principles, two-pass process, restraint, interface writing |\n159: | [`LICENSE.txt`](./LICENSE.txt) | Apache-2.0 license and attribution for the vendored Anthropic content |\n160: | [`sk-code`](../sk-code/README.md) | Implementation partner: builds and verifies the design for the target web surface |\n161: | [Skills Library](../README.md) | The skill catalog and routing front door |\n\n(End of file - total 161 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: sk-interface-design\ndescription: Aesthetic-direction skill for distinctive, intentional UI. Drives palette, typography, layout and motion choices that avoid templated AI defaults, then hands implementation to sk-code.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"interface design\"\n  - \"frontend design\"\n  - \"make it look good\"\n  - \"looks templated\"\n  - \"redesign\"\n---\n\n# sk-interface-design\n\n> Design interfaces that could not be mistaken for anyone else's: deliberate palette, typography, layout and motion grounded in the brief, with a critique pass that kills templated AI defaults before a line of code is written.\n\n---\n\n## 1. AT A GLANCE\n\n| Aspect | What you get |","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-interface-design/README.md","text":"---\ntitle: sk-interface-design\ndescription: Aesthetic-direction skill for distinctive, intentional UI. Drives palette, typography, layout and motion choices that avoid templated AI defaults, then hands implementation to sk-code.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"interface design\"\n  - \"frontend design\"\n  - \"make it look good\"\n  - \"looks templated\"\n  - \"redesign\"\n---\n\n# sk-interface-design\n\n> Design interfaces that could not be mistaken for anyone else's: deliberate palette, typography, layout and motion grounded in the brief, with a critique pass that kills templated AI defaults before a line of code is written.\n\n---\n\n## 1. AT A GLANCE\n\n| Aspect | What you get |\n|---|---|\n| **Use it for** | Aesthetic direction when building or reshaping UI: palette, typography, layout, motion, signature element, and interface copy |\n| **Invoke with** | \"interface design\", \"make it look good\", \"redesign\", \"looks templated\", \"hero section\" or auto-routing on design intent |\n| **Works on** | Any front-end surface, pairing with `sk-code` for implementation and `mcp-chrome-devtools` for screenshot self-critique |\n| **Produces** | A grounded design plan (token system + signature) critiqued against AI-default looks, then built to a responsive, accessible quality floor |\n\n---\n\n## 2. OVERVIEW\n\n### Why This Skill Exists\n\nAI-generated UI clusters around a handful of default looks that appear regardless of subject: cream-and-serif-and-terracotta, near-black-with-one-acid-accent, broadsheet-hairlines. They are safe, and they are why generated designs read as templated. A model building UI without explicit direction reaches for those defaults and for scattered motion that signals \"AI made this.\" This skill gives the framework a reusable, advisor-routable point of view: ground the design in the subject, make deliberate choices, take one justified risk, and critique the plan before building.\n\n### What It Does\n\nThe skill owns aesthetic direction, not implementation. It routes a design task through a two-pass process: ground the subject, brainstorm a compact token system (4-6 named colors, a display and body face, a layout concept, one signature element), then critique that plan against the known AI-default looks and revise anything generic with a stated reason. Only then does code get written, deriving every choice from the revised plan. It also carries interface-writing rules, because copy can make a design feel as templated as the visuals. Implementation is handed to `sk-code`, which builds and verifies against the detected web surface.\n\nThis is vendored from Anthropic's `frontend-design` skill (Apache-2.0). The full design guidance lives verbatim in `references/design_principles.md`, and the `SKILL.md` is a lean house-template router over it.\n\n---\n\n## 3. QUICK START\n\n**Step 1: Let the advisor route a design task here, or read the skill directly.**\n\n```bash\n# The advisor surfaces this skill on design intent. To read it directly:\ncat .opencode/skills/sk-interface-design/SKILL.md\n```\n\n**Step 2: Ground the subject and brainstorm a token system.**\n\nName one concrete subject, its audience, and the page's single job. Then draft a compact plan:\n\n```text\nColor:     4-6 named hex values drawn from the subject's world\nType:      a characterful display face (used with restraint) + a body face\nLayout:    a one-sentence concept + an ASCII wireframe\nSignature: the single element the page will be remembered by\n```\n\n**Step 3: Critique against the defaults, then build.**\n\n```text\nFor each part of the plan, ask: would I produce this for any similar brief?\nIf yes, it is a default, not a choice. Revise it and say what changed and why.\nThen build from the revised plan and hand implementation to sk-code.\n```\n\nFull guidance: [`references/design_principles.md`](./references/design_principles.md).\n\n---\n\n## 4. HOW IT WORKS\n\n### The Two-Pass Process\n\nThe skill never jumps straight to code. It grounds the subject, brainstorms a token system, and critiques that plan against three known AI-default looks before building. Anything that reads as a generic default gets revised with a stated reason, and every color and type decision in the build derives from the revised plan.\n\n### Restraint Is The Mechanism\n\nBoldness is spent in one place. The signature element is the one memorable move and everything around it stays quiet and disciplined. Decoration that does not serve the brief is cut, including numbered markers when the content is not actually a sequence, and motion that piles up rather than serving one orchestrated moment. The build meets a quiet quality floor: responsive to mobile, visible keyboard focus, reduced motion respected.\n\n### Copy Is Design Material\n\nWords exist to make an interface easier to use. The skill writes from the end user's side of the screen in active voice, keeps action names consistent across a flow, and treats errors and empty states as direction rather than mood.\n\n### Where The Detail Lives\n\n`references/design_principles.md` holds the verbatim guidance: grounding, the full design principles, the two-pass process with the AI-default calibration, restraint and self-critique, and interface writing.\n\n---\n\n## 5. INTEGRATION & NAVIGATION\n\n### When To Use This Skill\n\nReach for it whenever a task has a visual surface and the look should feel intentional: a new page or component, a redesign, a section variation, or any \"make it look good\" request. Skip it for pure logic or back-end work, and defer to the brief when the brief already pins the visual direction.\n\n### Related Skills\n\n| Skill | Relationship |\n|---|---|\n| `sk-code` | Owns implementation. This skill sets the look, and sk-code builds it to the detected web surface's standards and verifies it. |\n| `sk-code-review` | Audits the built UI against the standards sk-code enforces. |\n| `mcp-chrome-devtools` | Drives a real browser to screenshot the build for the self-critique step. |\n\n---\n\n## 6. TROUBLESHOOTING\n\n| What you see | Why | Fix |\n|---|---|---|\n| The output still looks templated | The plan was not critiqued against the AI-default looks, or a free axis was spent on a default | Run the critique pass in `design_principles.md` Section 4, then revise each generic part with a stated reason |\n| The design feels busy or \"AI-made\" | Boldness was spread across many elements, or motion piled up | Spend boldness on one signature element, cut one accessory, reduce to one orchestrated motion moment |\n| Copy undercuts the design | Labels describe the system, not what the user controls | Apply `design_principles.md` Section 6: active voice, end-user vocabulary, consistent action names |\n| The brief asked for a \"default\" look and the skill fought it | The brief's direction always wins | Follow the brief verbatim, since default-avoidance applies only to free axes |\n\n---\n\n## 7. FAQ\n\n**Q: Does this skill write the code?**\n\nA: No. It owns aesthetic direction and the design plan. `sk-code` owns implementation and verification for the detected web surface. The two pair: design here, build there.\n\n**Q: What are the \"AI-default looks\" it avoids?**\n\nA: Three clusters that appear regardless of subject: cream background with a high-contrast serif and terracotta accent, near-black with one bright acid accent, broadsheet hairlines with zero radius. They are legitimate for some briefs but are defaults, not choices. On a free axis, the skill does not spend it on one of these.\n\n**Q: What if the brief already specifies the look?**\n\nA: The brief wins, verbatim, even when it asks for one of the default looks. Default-avoidance only applies to axes the brief leaves free.\n\n**Q: Where did this come from?**\n\nA: It is vendored from Anthropic's official `frontend-design` skill under Apache-2.0. `LICENSE.txt` carries the full terms and attribution, and the guidance is preserved verbatim in `references/design_principles.md`.\n\n---\n\n## 8. VERIFICATION\n\n| Check | How to run it |\n|---|---|\n| Skill structure | `python3 .opencode/skills/sk-doc/scripts/package_skill.py .opencode/skills/sk-interface-design/` reports the skill valid |\n| README structure | `python3 .opencode/skills/sk-doc/scripts/validate_document.py .opencode/skills/sk-interface-design/README.md --type readme` reports zero issues |\n| Reference structure | `python3 .opencode/skills/sk-doc/scripts/validate_document.py .opencode/skills/sk-interface-design/references/design_principles.md --type reference` reports zero issues |\n| Advisor discovery | `node .opencode/bin/skill-advisor.cjs advisor_recommend --json '{\"prompt\":\"make this landing page look distinctive\"}' --warm-only --format json` lists `sk-interface-design` |\n\n---\n\n## 9. RELATED DOCUMENTS\n\n| Document | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| [`SKILL.md`](./SKILL.md) | Runtime instructions: WHEN TO USE, SMART ROUTING, HOW IT WORKS, RULES, REFERENCES (house template) |\n| [`references/design_principles.md`](./references/design_principles.md) | Full verbatim guidance: grounding, design principles, two-pass process, restraint, interface writing |\n| [`LICENSE.txt`](./LICENSE.txt) | Apache-2.0 license and attribution for the vendored Anthropic content |\n| [`sk-code`](../sk-code/README.md) | Implementation partner: builds and verifies the design for the target web surface |\n| [Skills Library](../README.md) | The skill catalog and routing front door |","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":161,"totalLines":161,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-interface-design/README.md","time":{"start":1781367756053,"end":1781367756115}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_09c9e28230c26120016a2d83cbd0e48191b97ea43b5097fbdd"}},"id":"prt_ec1cad510001BLW76vT4k8lgGs","sessionID":"ses_13e377e8fffeBUJXd02f1iJrmW","messageID":"msg_ec1caa389001VvtTL4IUCjJcnX"}}
